<includeonly>== Mounting partitions ==</includeonly>
When [[mount#Usage|mounting]] an [[ext2]], [[ext3]], [[ext4]], or [[wikipedia:ReiserFS|reiserfs]] partition, a few security related mount options can be applied in {{Path|/etc/fstab}}. The options are:

; <code>nosuid</code> : Ignores the SUID bit and make it just like an ordinary file.
; <code>noexec</code> : Prevents execution of files from this partition.
; <code>nodev</code> : Ignores devices.

Unfortunately, these settings can easily be circumvented by executing a non-direct path. However, setting {{Path|/tmp}} to <code>noexec</code> will stop the majority of exploits designed to be executed directly from {{Path|/tmp}}.

For example, a planning out {{Path|fstab}} file may look something like the following:

{{FileBox|filename=/etc/fstab|1=
/dev/sda1          /boot      ext2     noauto,relatime                     1 2
/dev/sda2          none       swap     sw                                  0 0
/dev/sda3          /          ext4     relatime,errors=remount-ro          0 1
/dev/sda4          /var       reiserfs notail,relatime,nodev,nosuid,noexec 0 2
/dev/sda5          /var/tmp   ext2     noatime,nodiratime,nodev,nosuid     0 2
/dev/sda6          /home      reiserfs notail,relatime,nodev,nosuid        0 2
/dev/sda7          /usr       reiserfs notail,relatime,nodev,ro            0 2
/dev/cdroms/cdrom0 /mnt/cdrom iso9660  noauto,ro                           0 0
none               /tmp       tmpfs    nodev,nosuid,noexec                 0 0
}}

{{Warning|Placing {{Path|/tmp}} in <code>noexec</code> mode can prevent certain legitimate scripts from executing properly.}}

{{Note|For disk quotas see the [[Security_Handbook/User/Group_limitations#Quotas|Quotas section]].}}

{{Note|Some programs (like {{Package|mail-mta/netqmail}}) will not be able to work properly if {{Path|/var}} has <code>noexec</code> and <code>nosuid</code>. Consider removing those options if they cause problems.}}

{{Note|{{Path|/usr}} is set to read-only mode because nothing is written there until updates are being applied. When it is time for system updates, remount the file system in read-write mode, updat,e and remount back to read-only. This small trick has the potential to keep a server more secure.}}
